<p><strong>Marriages between angels and women is just an absurd, ridiculous, heretical, and blasphemous
    teaching</strong></p>
<p><strong>Russellists have fabricated the blasphemous teaching that once there was a time in which many angels married
    women</strong>. This is totally false. Angels have neither power nor wisdom to create a human body; nor would God
    cooperate with them by creating a body with the sole purpose to commit such a horrid sin. In the "Watchtower", a
    magazine of the Russellists, they often present this teaching.</p>
<p> In order to support their error they present Gn 1-4, from which they have far fetched their fabrication. Sadly, they
    have "infected" true Christians, who are now believing the filthy idea. According to the "Governing Body" of the
    Russellists, a great number of angels, some how, incarnated themselves, and had "sons" with regular women. <strong>Not
        true</strong>.</p>
<p> To prop their teaching, Russellists allege that in Job 1: 6 the angels are called "sons of God", therefore, <strong>necessarily</strong>,
    those who were called "sons of God" in Genesis, have to also be angels. Let's first demonstrate biblically, and
    later using common sense, that this is another lie.</p>
<p> "<i>1 And it came to pass, when men began to multiply on the face of the earth, and daughters were born unto them, 2
    <strong>that the sons of God saw</strong> the daughters of men that they were fair; and they took them wives of all
    which they chose. 3 <strong>And the LORD said, My spirit shall not always strive with man</strong>, for that he also
    is flesh; yet his days shall be an hundred and twenty years. 4 <strong>There were giants in the earth in those days;
        and also after that, when the sons of God came in unto the daughters of men</strong>, and they bare children to
    them, the same became mighty men which were of old, men of renown. 5 And GOD saw that the wickedness of man was
    great in the earth, and that every imagination of the thoughts of his heart was only evil continually. 6 And it
    repented the LORD that he had made man on the earth, and it grieved him at his heart</i>." ( Gn 6: 1-4 )</p>
<p></p>
<p> "<i>Now there was a day when the sons of God came to present themselves before the LORD, <strong>and Satan came also
    among them</strong></i>." ( Job 1: 6 )</p>
<p><strong>In the Bible, human beings have been called "sons of God" many times more than the angels</strong>. Why then
    do the Russellists make believe that in Gn 6: 1-4 the phrase "sons of God" refers to angels and not men?</p>
<p><strong>Most probably, these men were called "sons of God", and these women were called "daughters of men", meaning
    that</strong> men who were believers and pious, married women who were unbelievers, carnal, sensual, and given to
    the flesh. Men did so because these women were gorgeous, beautiful, and paid no attention to their faith, and
    subsequently their soul. This interpretation of Gn 6: 1-2 agrees with the complaint God expresses in verse 3.
    Certainly so, after saying in verse 2 the wrongs of the so called "sons of God", God said: "<i>My spirit shall not
        always strive <strong>with man</strong></i>…". <strong>We see that God did not mention angels</strong>, who, in
    this case, would be the main subjects of the problem, ( if truly this teaching was right.)</p>
<p> "… <strong>the sons of God saw</strong> <i>the daughters of men that they were fair; and they took them wives of all
    which they chose. <strong>And the LORD said, My spirit shall not always strive with man</strong>, for that he also
    is flesh; yet his days shall be an hundred and twenty years</i>." ( Gn 6: 2-3 )</p>
<p><strong>Something else to consider, is that verse 2 does not say that "the sons of God" took a body of flesh and
    bones</strong>, as to be able to have sexual relations with women. It comes with the territory that if the phrase
    "sons of God" would refer to angels, the writer would explain that they took a body, because he had to know that no
    one would otherwise understand how an angel could have sex with a woman.</p>
<p><strong>It is far more logical to admit that the problem was caused by the believer's blinded lechery, leading them
    to marry without any regard for their religion</strong>. Because of the fact that every believer had taken this
    wrong path, we see that God considered it better to destroy that society, and start another with Noah, who was a man
    of great qualities.</p>
<p><strong>Now, to understand what I am about to say, it is necessary to realize that the 5th chapter of Genesis is a
    list of genealogies, inserted between Gn 4: 26 and 6: 1</strong>. If you jump from verse 4: 26 to 6: 1 you will not
    notice an interruption, but on the contrary, reading becomes more sequential and fluent. You will even see that
    chapter 5 begin by stating: "This is the book of the generations of Adam". This was probably a parchment inserted
    between Gn 4: 26 and 6: 1.</p>
<p> After understanding this previous explanation we realize that subsequent to saying in verse 4: 26 "<strong>And to
    Seth, to him also there was born a son; and he called his name Enos. Then men began to call upon the name of the
    LORD"</strong>, right afterwards in 6: 1-2 we see the complaint that "the sons of God" (descendants of faithful
    Enos, those who called themselves by the name of the Lord ), married the daughters of men, ( those who did not call
    themselves by the name of the Lord, maybe because they were descendants of Cain ). The importance of the problem is
    that by marrying believers to non believers, the society was going to corrupt entirely. All this proves that the
    phrase "sons of God" referred to men who were believers, and the phrase "daughters of men" referred to women who
    were unbelievers.</p>
<p><strong>It will become evident that human-beings are called "sons of God" over and over again, just by
